text:
¬†@cobrat5717¬† i just changed my name after i understood the philosophy of the Bungie verse, the videogame company that made Halo and Destiny. I grew up with them my whole life and now i understood why i like their games so much and partially why i am who i am now. It does have something to do with this argument too, the argument of choiche, let me explain briefly:
In their games they put a deep, hidden and interconnected narrative where the concept of light (altruism, complexity, life, giving, cycle of birth and death, technology, to forget the past to build the future, fundamental forces) is always fighting the concept of dark (egoism, simplicity, death, taking, eternity, ontological concepts, mind, memory). Every universe and timeline has these concepts manifest in different species or ways, in Destiny it's the traveller and the veil or maybe the Witness, in Halo it's the rings and the Flood, in Marathon it's the J'aro and the w'rkanter, or whatever they are called. The two forces often use powers of nature related to vibrations, especially in the Destiny franchise, like quantum fluctuations, quantum fields, in the lore, the fights between them create waves, and these waves create the universes.
In each universe, or multiverse, there is always one hero, the protagonist of the story, the player, which is Destiny, it has the power to change, through action, the balance between light and dark to its liking, it has the power to make what is almost impossible happen, it can control luck, it can rewind entire timelines, it can change the story, it lives in a single hero. Destiny is the player, the player has the power to try again every time after it looses, it is capable of winning against all odds by resetting the timeline where he died within the game, it always follows a story even if it's unlikely to happen, it has the power to choose how the world becomes.

I grew up playing these games, i like being someone with the power to change its own destiny, to choose what happens to me if i want. I realise that real life isn't like that, and many times luck controls our life, even if we fight it, and i don't like that. This name represents my hope that there is a way to change your own destiny after all, if not now, maybe in the future, and my attachement to the true power and potential of science (maybe by controlling the waves of the universe, quantum fields and such, we will be able to control our destiny in the future), while simultaneously giving a small love letter to Bungie.

I don't believe in destiny as an entity like the games, or as a real objective thing, i only refer to it as a man made concept that doesn't really exist, that represents basically everything that happened and will happen to something, almost like the arrow of time. To change it simply means taking an action that results in a different outcome, an outcome that you might prefer.

I don't want to die. I really don't want to. But "destiny" or simply chance, made me exist in an era where death is very likely to happen to everyone, even if not certain. Death is our likely destiny. I want to fight my destiny, i want to create a ripple, a wave, big enough to change that outcome, through science i might find what i'm looking for, and then, after that, to the stars, maybe trying to find something else and help it achieve the same dreams i had. I wish God would save me, but logically, i have more chance to survive if i help myself instead of waiting for a miracle.
I want to have a choiche because i realized i don't have one. I fight through the odds to change my fate.

text:
This is reminiscent of the far simpler aims of those that undertook the building of the tower of Babel.

There can be no immortality in a machine that wasn't mortal in the first place.

There's a vast difference between immortality and enhanced ways of recording memories. I can't imagine that such records could come close to actual memories. The way an AI system may regurgitate any memories must fall far short of an observer's interaction with the person whose memories they are. Unless AI can record the entire experience of a person, it won't come close in interacting with others as the person simulated or emulated would have done.

As impossible as that may be, no robotic AI system can come close to approximating the immortal life of a real person. People do not agree on what constitutes a soul, we can't even agree about the meaning of simple words, so it might be a good idea to see what AI can learn about humans and whether we 'understand' disparate things in anywhere near the same way as others.

I envisage great strides in the application of AI, given that there are also great dangers when it is in the hands of evil, careless and or ignorant individuals, but providing immortality to humans is probably nowhere near feasible.

As Elon Musk has rightly pointed out, we need controls in AI systems and legislation to address those that must be prevented from applying them for evil purposes. 

Guns are not evil and AI is not evil, but evil people can use them to further crime or evil objectives.

text:
¬†@sandybayes¬† 

In my understanding, AI differs fundamentally from systems using programs that control a computer's processing, precisely by way of specific instructions, because AI is designed to learn from the outcome of a chosen course and therefore not repeat a mistake made previously.  I believe we're largely in agreement in that the self-teaching and learning are essentially the same thing.

I agree that we can't predict where AI will lead and that human memory is not infallible; I'm concerned about my own.

We do seem to disagree about whether AI is a living being or an electronic system that in essence emulates the human brain, but works at a phenomenal speed and keeps track of vast amounts of data.  

I'm essentially saying that such capacity for receiving, processing, storing and retrieving data doesn't give it biology or emotion, no matter how closely it may emulate human behaviour. Such AI may exist in a processing unit that doesn't resemble a person or an aggregate of people.  A humanoid robot may function connected electronically to a brain or processor that is situated in a particular location and controls multiple robots in various locations, though it makes sense that both data storage and processing be distributed as determined to be necessary, by people or AI itself.

I'm interested to hear more of your views regarding AI, which in my experience may refer to artificial intelligence or ignorance, depending on its functioning.  I'm no expert, having done only elementary study in the late seventies, and some reading and observation in recent decades.

AI does not necessarily go beyond a powerful computer processor, except that it can draw conclusions based on massive volumes of data made available to it in various ways, and can change those conclusions or fine tune them without human intervention.
